metadata.name: Maps of Life #76
metadata.description:
Maps of Life is a generative cartographic experiment inspired by John Conway's Game of Life. The Game of Life is a zero-player game, its evolution is determined by its initial state, requiring no further input.

Maps of Life is a generative-player game, an algorithm that creates an initial random configuration and a collector that observes how the configuration evolves. Each mint produces a distinctly unique cartographic representation of an ideal town, with different color palettes, scales, and coordinates, an animation from its random birth to a stopped moment in time.

Maps of Life assumes that the built environment has a life of its own. And besides, only an automatic mind can name towns with Butterfly Names. Enjoy the view.

---
Interactivity:
Press LEFT and RIGHT arrows to speed-up or slow-down the evolution of the town.
Press "S" to save the current state to a PNG image.
If you want to change the resolution, just add "?res=XXX" to the end of the url.
---

(With these keys, you can possibly force the script to continue until its further completion. Could you get a deserted landscape?)

metadata.name: FX(T)RASH #392
metadata.description:
Imagine having Van Gogh's ear in a little box, getting your grubby hands on Banksy's stencils or Zancan's plotter! Well, here's something just as awesome - This is your chance to collect some trash straight from the King of Trash Art himself, Robness!

---

NOR44 & ROBNESS V2 JOIN FORCES TO CREATE A SPECIAL GENERATIVE PROJECT IN HONOR OF THE SECOND #TEZTRASH EVENT ON 12/21/22.  TEZTRASH IS A TEZOS COMMUNITY DAY WHEN THE CRYPTONATIVE ART MOVEMENT #TRASHART AND TRASH ART IN GENERAL IS CELEBRATED.  THE PREVIOUS TEZTRASH EVENT WAS A MONUMENTAL HIT ON TWITTER AND THIS TIME AROUND WE'VE DECIDED TO CONCOCT AN EPIC GENERATIVE DROP WHILST KEEPING THE TRASH ART ETHOS EMBEDDED IN THE WORK. HERE WE PLAY WITH THE NOTION OF 'TRASHING JPEGS' AND REINSERTING A PHYSICAL YET GENERATIVE REPRESENTATION OF THAT IDEA. ENJOY AND HAPPY TEZTRASH 2.0 DAY!

---

This generative artwork is composed of many layers of pre-rendered images with code utilized to stylize as well as randomly position, rotate and scale these elements, creating potentially infinite unique compositions resembling real-world outputs from a Photocopier/Copy Machine that's seen better days.

metadata.name: Composition #3 Patchwork Quilt #139
metadata.description:
Abstract, non-square(!) composition based on textural strokes and noise. There are a lot of possible combinations with all of the features! 50% chance of two different palette sets. 50% chance to have a brush textured background, and a 50% chance of it being horizontal or vertical. The quadtree rectangles are based on poisson disc sampling based on a simplex noise field. 90% of the compositions will be smaller boxes, and 10% will be large. For each box, there is a 10% chance that it will be oriented opposite of the rest.

Press ’s’ to save a screenshot.

metadata.name: Vertical World #94
metadata.description:
This artwork is a kind of my inquiry about ambiguous boundaries.
I was a child who liked to draw but always been dissatisfied with my work. Now through coding, I was able to create the "feelings" that I wanted to express. This work is not to imitate a certain landscape or painting style, but simply paint with different brushes, and cooperate with the randomness of the computer.
"I" creates horizontal order, and "computer" creates vertical disorder. My intention is to create
ambiguous visuals in a way that doesn't give specific images, but vague atmosphere.
The meaning is computer-generated and positioned through your eyes.
(It may take more time to render if you using Firefox browser.)

- Press [s] to save png image

Created by haxenfan using p5js.

metadata.name: Elswhere #190
metadata.description:
Perlin noise walks into a Julia set and finds itself Elswhere. X is real, Y is imaginary, or is it the other way around? 

Elswhere is a unique generative art series in which noise and fractal math are combined to create whimsical shapes and motifs, with an infinite number of variations. Made with p5js.

For each pixel, the noise values corresponding to the X and Y coordinates are computed and then used as the real and imaginary components for initializing a Julia set recursion. The pixel is colored based on the number of steps it takes for the recursion to reach its base case.

Keyboard controls:
[S] Save the current view.
[2] Render 2000x3000px image.
[4] Render 4000x6000px image.
[6] Render 6000x9000px image.

Created by Elsif, 2022.05

metadata.name: RIO #6
metadata.description:
Rio is a generative piece creating shapes based on trails. The size, position and amplitude of each square are generated for each token, along with the color theme.

Each reloading creates a different movement, as the algorithm underlying the piece is partially based on a noise.

At the end, the animation stop and the visual is created.

Created by Quentin Hocdé, between Riomaggiore and Siena (Italia).
